						<div class="postbody">Someone once mentioned a hybrid format, where you have your normal iNES file, and then just slap UNIF chunks to the end of the file. That seems reasonable to me. You maintain backwards compatibilty, so long as the file is not rejected for having extraneous data at the end. If the UNIF blocks exist, then they supercede anything in the iNES header. I can't think of anything off-hand where this would be troublesome... anyone?</div>

